analytic.title: Effect of Ti additions on mechanical properties of NbMoTaW and VNbMoTaW refractory high entropy alloys

biblStruct.note: Received 28 September 2016 Received in revised form 23 December 2016 Accepted 10 January 2017

application.desc: GROBID - A machine learning software for extracting information from scholarly documents

div.p: With Ti addition in a NbMoTaW alloy, a new refractory high entropy alloy (HEA) of TiNbMoTaW was developed. It has been found that this HEA possesses single body-centered cubic (BCC) phase structure, and could sustain the phase structure even after annealing at 1200 C for 24 h. In comparison with the mechanical properties of the NbMoTaW and VNbMoTaW HEAs, the room-temperature yield strengths and compressive plastic strains of the TiNbMoTaW and TiVNbMoTaW HEAs are significantly enhanced. In particular, the TiNbMoTaW and TiVNbMoTaW HEAs also show very promising high temperature strength. Their yield strengths are as high as ~586 and ~659 MPa at 1200 C, respectively. The present results indicate that Ti addition is beneficial to the strength and the compressive ductility of the refractory HEAs at room-temperature. It is suggested that the present refractory HEAs possess the potentials in applications of high temperature structure materials.

div.head: Introduction
div.p: Containing five or more components in equimolar or nearequimolar ratios, HEAs, firstly named by J.W. Yeh in 2004 [1], have been considered as a new class of advanced materials in recent years. Due to a combination of high entropy, lattice distortion, sluggish diffusion and Cocktail effects [2,3], HEAs attract lots of attention and hold promises for a variety of applications, such as high strength alloys [4e18], corrosion resistant alloys [19e22], wear resistant alloys [23e25], and diffusion barriers [26,27].

Among their different purposes, the most attractive one for HEAs is that they could be served as high strength alloys at elevated temperature. As already confirmed in the work of Senkov and his colleagues, the refractory HEAs possess higher strengths than those of widely used superalloys such as Inconel 718 and Haynes 230 at high temperature (>1000 C), which is attributed to their high melting temperature and solid solution strengthening [5]. In response to the need for high-temperature load-bearing materials, several refractory HEA systems with a single-phase body-centeredcubic (bcc) solid solution structure, including Nb-Ta-Mo-W [5,28,29], Nb-Ti-Zr [4,6,8,30e35] and Nb-Ti-V [7,15], have been successfully developed.

Among these reported refractory HEAs, the NbMoTaW and VNbMoTaW HEAs have received the most attentions and been extensively studied due to that they possess the yield strength higher than 500 MPa at 1200 C [4,6e8,33,36]. However, the NbMoTaW and VNbMoTaW HEAs are brittle (showing very limited compressive plasticity of about 2% at room temperature [5]), which would limit their broad applications. Thus, improving their ductility is very important and meaningful.

It is well known that alloying is an effective method to improve mechanical properties of alloys [37]. Here, alloying method has been used to enhance the plasticity of the NbMoTaW and VNbMoTaW HEAs. Titanium and their alloys possess high specific strength, good ductility and excellent high temperature properties. Therefore, Ti additions in the NbMoTaW and VNbMoTaW HEAs might induce unique alloying effect in improving their mechanical properties. In addition to an earlier reported refractory high entropy alloy TiVNbMoTaW [29], a new refractory high entropy alloys of TiNb-MoTaW was developed in the present work. The effect of Ti additions on their structural stability and mechanical properties was investigated at both room temperature and elevated temperature.

div.head: Experimental procedures
div.p: TiNbMoTaW and TiVNbMoTaW HEAs were prepared by arc melting of equimolar mixtures of the corresponding elements. The purities of Ti, V, Nb, Mo, Ta and W are higher than 99.96 mass %. To ensure elemental homogeneity in the ingots, each ingot was remelted five times. The ingots were cut into appropriate shapes for investigating their microstructure and mechanical properties. The structures of the samples in both as-cast and annealed conditions were characterized by X-ray diffraction (XRD, Rigaku D/max-RB) using a Cu Ka radiation. WDW-50 testing machine was employed to measure the room temperature mechanical properties of both alloys at a strain rate of 1 Â 10 À3 /s using the cuboid samples with a dimension of 5 mm Â 5 mm Â 7.5 mm. The hightemperature compression tests were carried out with Glee-ble3500 thermal simulator using samples with dimensions of 5 mm Â 5 mm Â 7.5 mm. Before test, the chamber was evacuated to 1 Â 10 À3 Pa and refilled with argon. The samples were heated at a heating rate of 10 C/s by electrical resistance heating method, soaked at the test temperature for 3 min under 100 N load control, and then compressed at a strain rate of 1 Â 10 À3 s À1 . The flatness of the polished cross-section and the chemical compositions were examined by Quanta 200 FEG scanning electron microscope (SEM) and Energy Dispersive Spectrometer (EDS). The hardness and elastic constants of both alloys were measured by using MH-3 micro-Vickers hardness tester and Quasar RUSpec 4000 ultrasonic resonance spectrometer, respectively. The samples for measurement have dimensions of 3 mm Â 3 mm Â 3 mm. The frequency for measurements of the elastic constants ranged from 300 to 700 kHz.

div.head: Results and discussions
div.p: Fig. 1a shows the XRD spectra of the as-cast TiNbMoTaW HEA sample and the one annealed at 1200 C for 24 h. Sharp diffraction peaks are observed in the as-cast sample, which have been indexed as peaks resulted from a single BCC phase with a lattice constant of 3.240 Å. Through indexing the XRD spectrum of the annealed sample, it confirms that except a single BCC phase with a lattice constant of 3.225 Å, no any other phase has been found under the resolution of the XRD analysis method. This result indicates the Ticontaining HEAs possess excellent thermal stability even at 1200 C.

Phase selection and phase stability in HEAs are important topics due to the complicated interaction among multi-elements. Hitherto, several parameters of U, g and VEC have been proposed to predict the phase stability in HEAs. They are defined by formula (1), ( 2) and (3), respectively as following:

div.p: where DH mix is the enthalpy of mixing and DS mix is the entropy of mixing, (T m ) i is the melting temperature of the ith element. r i is the atomic radius of the ith element, r S and r L are smallest and largest atomic sizes, respectively. While (VEC) i is the valance electron concentration of the ith atom. c i in the formula all above is the atomic percentage of the ith element.

Based on the calculation, the obtained values of the parameters for the TiNbMoTaW HEA are: U ¼ 13.0, g ¼ 1.079 and VEC ¼ 5.2. It is known that U > 1.1 and g < 1.175 is required for solid solution formation and BCC phases are more stable when VEC<6.87

Consequently, the structure of the TiNbMoTaW HEA is supposed to be a stable BCC solid solution phase. Our experimental results indeed agree well with the prediction. Meanwhile, the as-cast TiVNbTaMoW HEA was also confirmed to possess a single BCC phase with a lattice constant of 3.212 Å by XRD analysis (Fig. 1b), which coincides with the reported result [29]. Similarly, the initial single BCC phase structure is retained even after the alloy was annealed at 1200 C for 24 h (Fig. 1b). The peaks are shifted to high diffraction angles a little bit by yielding a lattice constant of 3.209 Å, indicating a structural relaxation induced by the annealing treatment. The result implies that this HEA possesses high-temperature structural stability as well. Formation of stable single BCC phases was also reported in the NbMoTaW and VNbMoTaW HEAs [5]. Therefore, additions of Ti are supposed to play no detrimental effect on the structural stability of these refractory HEAs at elevated temperature.

The micro-hardness of the two as-cast and annealed alloys was measured by a MH-3 micro-Vickers hardness tester. The hardness of the as-cast TiNbMoTaW HEA is 498.7 ± 8.3 HV, while it increases to 510.9 ± 5.7 HV after annealing at 1200 C for 24 h. Meanwhile, the hardness values are 510.3 ± 6.0 HV and 522.3 ± 11.2 HV for the TiVNbMoTaW HEA in the as-cast and annealed states, respectively. The increase of hardness after annealing treatment of these HEAs indicates that structure relaxation of refractory HEAs resulted by annealing doesn't result in softening. Similar phenomenon was also been observed in an AlNbTiV HEA [7]. The hardness of the TiVNb-MoTaW HEA is slightly larger than that of the TiNbMoTaW HEA, similar to the result reported in the NbMoTaW and VNbMoTaW HEAs [5]. This can be explained by the solid solution model of HEAs [41]. In addition, the hardness and the lattice constants for the BCC phase in the TiVNbMoTaW HEA are consistent with the reported values [29].

The elastic constants of the two alloys were also measured. The TiNbMoTaW HEA possesses a bulk modulus of 139 GPa, a shear modulus of 59 GPa, a Young's modulus of 156 GPa and a Possion's ratio of 0.31. Additionally, the TiVNbTaMoW HEA possesses a bulk modulus of 150 GPa, a shear modulus of 62 GPa, a Young's modulus of 164 GPa and a Possion's ratio of 0.32.

The engineering stress-strain curves of the TiNbMoTaW and TiVNbTaMoW HEAs at room temperature and elevated temperatures are shown in Fig. 2 and the mechanical properties of both alloys are given in Table 1. The yield stress (s 0.2 ), the peak stress (s p ) and the plastic strain (ε p ) of the TiNbMoTaW HEA at room temperature are 1343 MPa, 2005 MPa and 14.1%, respectively (Fig. 2a).
At 600 C, its s 0.2 decreases to 689 MPa whereas ε p increases to 35.4%. With increasing temperature, s 0.2 further decreases steadily from 689 MPa at 600 C to 586 MPa at 1200 C (Fig. 2a).

The TiVNbTaMoW HEA exhibits a s 0.2 value of 1515 MPa, a s p value of 2135 MPa and p ¼ 10.6% at room temperature (Fig. 2b). Increasing temperature to 600 C leads to a decrease of the s 0.2 e973 MPa, while its ε p increases to 18.8%. As shown in both Fig. 2 and Table 1, further increasing temperature to 1200 C results in a continuous decrease of the s 0.2 e659 MPa, while the ε p reaches a maximum of 23.7% measured at 1000 C and then decreases to 8.4% when deformed at 1200 C (Fig. 2b).

The two alloys exhibit good mechanical properties, which are beneficial for the improvement of the strength of the crystalline materials due to their relatively high strength and high solid solution hardening (SSH) effect. In addition, the strong atomic bonding inherited from the refractory elements can also enhance the strength of the alloys especially at elevated temperatures.

To evaluate the effect of Ti additions on the mechanical properties of the refractory HEAs, the mechanical properties of the NbMoTaW and VNbMoTaW HEAs are also displayed in Table 1. In comparison with the mechanical performance of the NbMoTaW and VNbMoTaW HEAs at room temperature, both the strength and the ductility of the TiNbMoTaW and TiVNbMoTaW HEAs are enhanced due to Ti additions (Table 1). This further confirms that Ti element is a good choice for alloying of the refractory HEAs in the present study.

The enhanced strength of the studied alloys after Ti addition primarily originates from the SSH effect in HEAs proposed by Isaac Toda-Caraballo et al. [42]. The model was developed from the Labush's approach of the SSH in binary alloy systems [43]. In the model, a parameter ds dXi was defined as in Eq. Where s Ti is the interatomic spacing of pure Ti and s NbMoTaW is the average interatomic spacing of the equiatomic quaternary NbMo-TaW system. The hardening effect of Ti additions in the studied alloys can be explained in terms of the parameter ds dXi 1 s , which represents the principal factor for the SSH model. Basically, the projective area of the (X i , ds dXi 1 s ) is proportional to the hardening contribution of each element. For the NbMoTaW HEA, the sum of the areas for Nb, Mo, Ta and W with the content of 0.25 is 1.4 Â 10 À3 , while for the TiNb-MoTaW HEA, with the content of Ti, Nb, Mo, Ta and W to be 0.2, it is 3.4 Â 10 À3 . With Ti additions, the hardending effect is significantly enhanced. Similarly, the incorporation of Ti in the quinary VNbMoTaW HEA also hardens the alloy as predicted by the model. The sum of the areas for the VNbMoTaW HEA is 8.4 Â 10 À4 , while for the TiVNbMoTaW HEA it equals to 1.8 Â 10 À3 , demonstrating there exists strain hardening effect induced by Ti addition as well.

The SEM image of the as-cast TiNbMoTaW HEA is shown in Fig. 3. The chemical compositions of the dendrite arms and the inter-dendrite regions were determined by the EDS analysis. The results shown in Table 2 indicate that the dendrite arms of the TiNbMoTaW HEA are enriched with Ta and W and are Ti-poor, while the inter-dendrite regions are enriched with Ti and Nb and are Wdeficient. The Mo content in the inter-dendrite regions is a little bit higher than that in the dendrite arms. The elemental distributions in the microstructure are clearly shown in the chemical mappings of each element (Fig. 4). These mapping results evidenced that Ti alloying element segregates in the inter-dendrite areas.

It is accepted that the stress is easily accumulated at interdendrite regions during the compression tests. The segregation of ductile elements such as Ti and Nb at the inter-dendrite regions favors accommodation of the increased strain. Thus, the roomtemperature compressive strain is significantly enhanced. The similar results were also reported in the Cu-containing HEAs [44,45]. Twinning activity in HEAs may also contribute to the good ductility by reducing the stress localization. The shear modulus of the TiNbMoTaW and TiVNbMoTaW HEAs are 59 GPa and 62 GPa, respectively. The critical twinning stress (s ctw ) values of the two alloys are estimated to be 913 MPa and 960 MPa, respectively. Both s ctw values are much lower than s 0.2 values for the two alloys, thus implying activation of a large quantity of deformation twinning [4,31]. In addition to Ti and Nb, V easily segregates at the interdendrite regions as well [29]. Despite the beneficial effect on the ductility from Ti and Nb segregation, V usually leads to a detrimental effect on the ductility. Consequently, the room-temperature compressive plasticity of the TiVNbTaMoW HEA is lower than that of the TiNbMoTaW HEA.

div.head: Conclusions
div.p: With Ti additions, a new refractory TiNbMoTaW high entropy alloy with a single BCC phase structure has been developed. The Ticontaining HEAs possess high thermal stability and sustain a BCC phase even when annealed at 1200 C for 24 h. Owing to the Ti alloying in the NbMoTaW and VNbMoTaW HEAs, the TiNbMoTaW and TiVNbTaMoW HEAs show enhanced strength and ductility. The room-temperature yield strengths of the TiNbMoTaW and TiVNb-MoTaW HEAs are 1343 MPa and 1515 MPa, respectively. Meanwhile, their compressive plastic strains at room temperature are above 10%. The effect of Ti additions on the mechanical properties of these HEAs can be interpreted in terms of a solid solution hardening model. It has been found that both the TiNbMoTaW and TiVNbTaMoW HEAs exhibit yield strengths higher than 550 MPa at 1200 C. The high-temperature mechanical performance of these two HEAs makes them to be potential materials for hightemperature applications.
